name: Alan Bush
aliases: The Massed Choirs of the Glasgow Socialist Singers and the Glasgow Y.C.L. Choir conducted by Alan Bush
comments: Composer, pianist, conductor, teacher and political activist. A two-year period in Berlin in 1929 to 1931, early in the Nazi Party's rise to power, cemented Bush's political convictions and moved him from the mainstream Labour Party to the Communist Party of Great Britain which he joined in 1935. He wrote several large-scale works in the 1930s, and was heavily involved with workers' choirs for whom he composed pageants, choruses and songs. In 1936 Bush was one of the founders of the Workers' Musical Association (WMA), and became its first chairman. In 1939 the Topic Records label was set up as an offshoot of the Workers' Musical Association. Bush was heavily involved as arranger and musician in the label's output from the very beginning to 1950.

name: Amanda Lear
comments: Born in Saigon in 1939 as Alain Tap, although all of this is disputed. Birth place is sometimes assumed to be Hong Kong, and other possible birth years are 1941 and 1946. Lear started a career as a fashion model in the mid-1960s and came to public attention as the model for the cover of Roxy Music's For Your Pleasure .  Although she was Salvador Dali's muse and mistress throughout the 1960s and 1970s, she was romantically linked to Brian Jones and was the inspiration for Miss Amanda Jones .  Lear also carried on a year long affair with David Bowie , who paid for singing and dancing lessons, launching her musical career in disco and Euro-pop.

name: Carola Neher
comments: Actress born in Munich. In 1926 she went to Berlin to work with Bertolt Brecht, who wrote the role of Polly Peachum in "Die Dreigroschenoper" for her, but late in rehearsals her husband died and she was unable to appear at the premiere. But she acted the role of Polly in the later performances. Brecht wrote several roles for her like Lilian Holiday in Happy End . She left Germany after Adolf Hitler's ascension to power in spring 1933, emigrated to Prague but went on to the Soviet Union in 1934. In 1936 - during the Great Purge - she was arrested and sentenced to ten years in prison, sent to a gulag near Orenburg, where she died of typhus on July 26, 1942.
